{
  "text": "We assessed the two processes of desensitization of TRPV1 channels [CITATION_1] . NG neurons were studied under perforated patch voltage clamp, held at a continuous voltage of À60 mV. In these experiments, we used a maximal concentration of Cap to maximize both processes. We recorded robust acute desensitization and strong tachyphylaxis of TRPV1 currents in response to a saturating concentration of Cap (1 mM) given 5 min apart in sensory neurons from WT mice ( Figure 9A ). However, in the presence of the specific Ca V 1.2-channel blocker, nifedipine, both phenomena were profoundly reduced ( Figure 9B ), with the most dramatic effect on tachyphylaxis, suggesting the critical role of co-associated Ca V 1.2 channels in TRPV1-channel behavior. Most notably, the dramatic effects of Ca V 1.2 activity were manifest at À60 mV, some 30 mV more negative than the threshold voltage for opening of these channels, which was verified for the neurons studied in this work (Figure S5D ). To exclude the direct effect of nifedipine on TRPV1 channels, we performed experiments on CHO cells transfected with only TRPV1 and observed no difference in desensitization of TRPV1 current by nifedipine ( Figures S5A-S5C ).",
  "correct_citation": {
